    "summary": "YES spoilers, NOT FINE — reveals experiential payoffs",
    "content": "**Q1: YES** — The Preface contains spoilers. The Experiential Sequences section (the three examples) reveals the philosophical payoffs of Essays 3, 4, and 7. Specifically: it tells the reader that \"no one who owns a cat has ever felt absurd about it\" (the conclusion the reader is meant to arrive at themselves), it describes the reversal of the dao-de-ren-yi-li hierarchy (the experience the reader is meant to undergo), and it explains the meme sentence contrast (the demonstration of understanding vs. non-understanding that the reader is meant to feel firsthand).\n\n**Q2: NOT FINE** — These are precisely the kind of spoilers that undermine the work's method. The Preface correctly identifies that \"the experience IS the argument\" and that experiential sequences \"cannot be rearranged, summarized, or abstracted without destroying them\" — and then proceeds to summarize them. The Preface should describe the METHOD (the author designs experiential sequences) without revealing the CONTENT of specific sequences. It can say \"Essay 3 arranges three cases of apparently meaningless labor in a specific order; the progression is the philosophical payload\" without telling the reader what they will discover at the end. The current version gives away the punchline of at least three essays."
  }
